<\list>


<s1 id=ToOpenAnImageFileTA>To Open an Image File
	<idx>opening, image file<\idx>
	<idx>image file, opening<\idx>

With Image Viewer, you can view, edit, print, and translate the file formats 
of monochrome and color images and PostScript 
files.  See <xref ImageVFileFormats> for a list of the file formats
that Image Viewer can
open.  
See <xref ToViewADocumentFileTA> to learn how to view PostScript files.

<list order>
<item>Choose Open from the File menu.
<p>The Open dialog box appears.

<newline>&empty;

<figure nonumber entity=ImageV-Open-Dialog>
<\figure>

<newline>&empty;

<item>To navigate among and display the contents of folders, double-click 
a folder in the Folders list.
<item>Select an image file from the Files list or type the image file 
name in the Enter file name field.
<item>Click OK to open the image file.
<p>The image file is displayed in the View window.
<\list>

<procedure>Using Drag and Drop

<p>You can also open an image file using drag and drop.

<list bullet>
<item>If Image Viewer is already running, drop an image file icon on an open Image Viewer
window.
<\list>

<list order>
<item>Drag an image file icon from File Manager and drop it on the workspace.
<item>Press or click mouse button 3 over the image file icon on the workspace and 
choose Open from the Workspace Object menu.
<p>The image file is displayed in Image Viewer's View window.
<item>To remove the file icon from the workspace, click mouse
button 3 on the icon and choose Remove From Workspace from the popup
menu. 
<\list>


<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToViewADocumentFileTA>
<item> <xref ToPrintSingleCopyTA>
<item> <xref ToDisplayFileInformationTA>
<item> <xref ImageVFileFormats>
<\list>


<s1 id=ToViewADocumentFileTA>To Open a PostScript File
	<idx>PostScript file, viewing<\idx>
	<idx>viewing, PostScript file<\idx>
	<idx>opening, PostScript file<\idx>

<p>With Image Viewer, you can view PostScript files as well as image files.
<list order>
<item>Choose Open from the File menu.

<newline>&empty;

<!-- show Image Viewer Open File Chooser -->
<figure nonumber entity=ImageV-Open-Dialog>
<\figure>

<newline>&empty;

<item>To navigate among and display the contents of folders, choose a folder from the Folders list.
<item>Choose a PostScript file from the Files list or type the
PostScript file name in the Enter file name field.
<item>Click OK to open the PostScript file.
<p>The PostScript file is displayed in Image Viewer's View window.
<\list>

<procedure>Using Drag and Drop
<p>You can also open a PostScript file using drag and drop.

<list bullet>
<item>If Image Viewer is already running, drag the PostScript file
icon from File Manager and drop it on an open Image Viewer window.
<\list>

<list order>
<item>Drag the PostScript file icon from File Manager and drop it on the Workspace.
<item>Click or press mouse button 3 over the PostScript file icon on the 
Workspace and choose Open from the Workspace Object menu.
<p>Image Viewer is started up and the PostScript file is displayed in
Image Viewer's View window.
<item>To remove the file icon from the workspace, click mouse
button 3 on the icon and choose Remove From Workspace from the popup
menu. 
<\list>


<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToOpenAnImageFileTA>
<item> <xref ToPrintSingleCopyTA>
<item> <xref ToDisplayFileInformationTA>
<item> <xref ImageVFileFormats>
<\list>


<s1 id=PagingThroughTA>To Page through a PostScript File
	<idx>pages, viewing<\idx>
	<idx>viewing, pages<\idx>

<p>You can page through a PostScript file using the Page slider or the Page 
arrow buttons.

<newline>&empty;
<!-- <p gentity=ImageV-Tool-Bar gposition=left>&empty; -->
<figure nonumber entity=ImageV-Tool-Bar>
<\figure>

<newline>&empty;

<p>Using your keyboard, you can view:
<list bullet>
<item>The first page by pressing Home
<item>The next page by pressing PgDn or Return
<item>The previous page by pressing PgUp, Back Space, or Del[ete]
<item>The last page by pressing End
<\list>

<newline> &empty;
<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ViewingSpecificTA>
<\list>


<s1 id=ViewingSpecificTA>To View a Specific Page
<p>To view specific pages of a PostScript file, choose Page Overview from the View 
menu.
<note>If the Page Overview menu item is unavailable, Image Viewer is loading the 
information for the Page Overview dialog box.  For a long document, this may 
take a while.<\note>
<newline>&empty;
<p>As shown in the following illustration, the Page Overview window uses 
thumbnail page buttons to show simple renderings of the pages in a document.
You can double-click a page button to view a page, or type the page number
in the Go To Page field.

<newline>&empty;
<figure nonumber entity=ImageV-Page-Overview>
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref PagingThroughTA>
<item> <xref ToViewADocumentFileTA>
<\list>


<s1 id=ToReversePageOrderTA>To Reverse Page Order
	<idx>page order, reversing<\idx>
	<idx>reversing page order<\idx>

<p>The page order of a PostScript file is often reversed when the file is prepared for
printing&emdash;this is a convenient way to collate a document on printers that
produce pages printed side up.
<p>To reverse the page order of a document you are viewing:

<list order>
<item>Choose Page Viewing Controls from the View menu.
<p>The Page Viewing Controls dialog box appears.

<newline>&empty;
<figure nonumber entity=ImageV-Viewing-Controls>
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<item>Select the order in which you want the pages of the current document displayed
(First Page First or Last Page First).
<item>Click OK to apply your choices and close the dialog box.
<\list>

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToViewADocumentFileTA>
<item> <xref ImageVPageViewingControlsDialog>
<\list>


<s1 id=ToChangeSizeOfDisplayedPageTA>To Change the Size of the Displayed Page
	<idx>displayed page, changing size of<\idx>
	<idx>changing size, of displayed page<\idx>

<p>The page description language used to create some documents may not
include page size information.  This can cause page boundaries to display incorrectly.
<p>To change the displayed page size:

<list order>
<item>Choose Page Viewing Controls from the View menu.
<p>The Page Viewing Controls dialog box appears.

<newline>&empty;

<figure nonumber entity=ImageV-Viewing-Controls>
<\figure>

<newline>&empty;

<item>Select the size of the page you want to use for displaying the current document.
<item>Click OK to apply your choices and close the dialog box.
<\list>

See <xref ImageVPrintDialog> for information on changing the size of the printed page.

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToViewADocumentFileTA>
<item> <xref ImageVPrintDialog>
<\list>


<s1 id=ToDisplayFileInformationTA>To Display File Information
	<idx>image information, displaying<\idx>
	<idx>file information, displaying<\idx>
	<idx>displaying, file information<\idx>
	<idx>displaying, image information<\idx>

<list bullet> 
<item> To view file information, choose Image Info from the View menu.
<\list>

<p>Image Viewer provides the following information about the currently displayed file:

<list bullet tight>
<item>Height and width of the image or page&emdash;in inches,
centimeters, and pixels
<item>Number of colors
<item>File size
<item>File format
<\list>


